r size=1> I found this on the necro.eqclasses.com site. I figured I'd post it so anyone who doesn't know about it can be informed.<br>
<br>
STARTS HERE: <br>
<br>
Im reposting this from our server board. I wrote it. It happened on Bertoxx.<br>
<br>
<br>
Anyone who has been around for a while knows of an old bug where if someone is zoning, you can accidently create a char of the same name as them if you just have bad luck and timing. Somewhere along the line, someone did this and found that doing so causes you to be able to access the character whose name you duplicated. Once this was discovered it was only a matter of time until people started using it to screw people over. And they did, a lot. Despite Verant's denial of hacking accounts, this went on for a while. Well, Verant stated officially that they &quot;fixed&quot; this bug like 5 or 6 months ago and that duping someone's character was no longer possible. <br>
<br>
<br>
On Tuesday night, I zoned into Overthere to res a friend of mine. I ran across a person I had met before when travelling with friends. She is a level 34 enchanter named Vena. A very nice person, and always willing to help out. We chatted for a bit, I ressed my friend, and then Vena noticed that she was level 1 according to /who on the zone. I did a /who all Vena and came up with 2 of them. A level 1 Vena in Overthere, and a level 1 Vena in Nektulous. <br>
<br>
<br>
Now, since I heard of the zoning bug, I have always had my chars on my friends list, so that I can see if there are two copies of me out and running around. Once I saw this, I knew exactly what was happening. Either someone was incredibly unlucky and created a char by accident or Vena was in the process of being hacked. So I told her to petition immediatley and explained what was happening to her. Well, by the time her petition got through the queue, the person had logged, but the GMs noted the incident and set a note (or whatever they do) on her account. <br>
<br>
<br>
So I logged in yesterday, and Vena sent me a /tell almost immediately, thanking me. Apparently, this person had logged into her account yesterday, and was in the process of stripping her items when Crassus and Nurmatin (who both had her on their friends list) noticed that she was level 1 (she's supposed to be level 34 as I mentioned) and both of them /petitioned immediately. <br>
<br>
<br>
The GMs caught the person in the act, and got their station name. They restored Vena's account and basically things were ok. Yay, the good guys win, strictly due to player diligence. <br>
<br>
<br>
If this hadn't gone down the way it had, Vena would have most likely had a huge headache dealing with Verant and their &quot;guilty until proven innocent&quot; policy. At the very best they would have found the logs that proved her char was stripped, and restored it, timeframe 1-2 weeks or so. At the very worst, they would have accused her of giving out her password to someone else and banned her for doing so. Don't think it happens? Read the general news board. It does, and even admitting that your parents have your password in case of emergencies, even if your parents don't own a computer, can get you penalized by the system. <br>
<br>
<br>
Verant claims that no hacking can happen. And it does. They will automatically try to pin the blame on the owner of the account before considering the flaws in their security and bugs in their code. Your only choice is to protect yourself from uncaring and uninformed Verant employees and malicious people who appear to be much more devious than the Verant programmers. You're in Verants world now, and you're unprotected. The only way to protect yourself from this particular type of attack is to put yourself on your friends list, use it often, and to make sure that everyone knows if there is ever 2 of your chars on to petition and GET IT ON RECORD. <br>
<br>
<br>
I'd like to say thanks to the GMs who caught this account doing the hacking, but I'd also like to point out to all of you employees reading this, that your system is NOT secure. Most likely the person/people doing this has/have several accounts (how do you think they knew she was zoning?) and most likely, they will do it again. This time they were caught by sheer luck, and player intervention. The next victim will most likely not be so lucky. <br>
<br>
<br>
And aren't we all glad this bug was announced as fixed? <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Lets keep an eye out for each other and shut these guys down!<br>
